"use strict";(self.webpackChunkwebsite=self.webpackChunkwebsite||[]).push([["6372"],{76616:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api","metadata":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api","source":"@site/i18n/fr/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog-articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api/index.mdx","title":"useSyncExternalStore - L\'API React sous-estim\xe9e","description":"Tu as peut-\xeatre entendu parler de useSyncExternalStore(), un nouveau hook de React 18 permettant de s\'abonner \xe0 des sources de donn\xe9es externes. Il est souvent utilis\xe9 en interne par les biblioth\xe8ques de gestion d\'\xe9tat - comme Redux - pour mettre en place un syst\xe8me de s\xe9lecteurs.","date":"2022-09-06T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":4.975,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Editeur - Mainteneur de Docusaurus","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","page":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/authors/slorber"},"socials":{"x":"https://x.com/sebastienlorber"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api","title":"useSyncExternalStore - L\'API React sous-estim\xe9e","authors":["slorber"],"date":"2022-09-06T00:00:00.000Z","twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/t/articles/useSyncExternalStore","image":"./social-card.png","isTranslationMissing":false},"unlisted":false,"nextItem":{"title":"Records & Tuples for React","permalink":"/fr/articles/records-and-tuples-for-react"}},"content":"Tu as peut-\xeatre entendu parler de [`useSyncExternalStore()`](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#usesyncexternalstore), un nouveau hook de React 18 permettant de s\'abonner \xe0 des **sources de donn\xe9es externes**. Il est souvent utilis\xe9 en interne par les biblioth\xe8ques de gestion d\'\xe9tat - comme [Redux](https://github.com/reduxjs/react-redux/pull/1808) - pour mettre en place un **syst\xe8me de s\xe9lecteurs**.\\n\\nMais pourquoi pas utiliser `useSyncExternalStore()` dans ton propre code?\\n\\nDans cet article interactif, je souhaite te pr\xe9senter un probl\xe8me : **les hooks React qui retournent trop et d\xe9clenchant des re-renders inutiles**. On va aussi voir comment `useSyncExternalStore()` peut \xeatre une bonne solution.\\n\\n![social card](./social-card.png)\\n\\n\x3c!-- truncate --\x3e\\n\\n<SubscribeFormEmbed />\\n\\nimport {\\n  App,\\n  AppFixed,\\n  ScrollApp,\\n} from \\"@site/articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api/demos\\";\\n\\n## Les hooks qui retournent trop\\n\\nNous pouvons illustrer le probl\xe8me avec [`useLocation()`](https://reactrouter.com/en/main/hooks/use-location) de React-Router.\\n\\nCe hook retourne un objet avec de nombreux attributs (`pathname`, `hash`, `search`...), mais tu n\'as pas toujours besoin de toutes ces donn\xe9es. Le simple fait d\'appeler ce hook va d\xe9clencher des re-renders \xe0 chaque fois qu\'un de ces attributs est mis \xe0 jour.\\n\\nPrenons cette application:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction CurrentPathname() {\\n  const { pathname } = useLocation();\\n  return <div>{pathname}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction CurrentHash() {\\n  const { hash } = useLocation();\\n  return <div>{hash}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction Links() {\\n  return (\\n    <div>\\n      <Link to=\\"#link1\\">#link1</Link>\\n      <Link to=\\"#link2\\">#link2</Link>\\n      <Link to=\\"#link3\\">#link3</Link>\\n    </div>\\n  );\\n}\\n\\nfunction App() {\\n  return (\\n    <div>\\n      <CurrentPathname />\\n      <CurrentHash />\\n      <Links />\\n    </div>\\n  );\\n}\\n```\\n\\n<App />\\n\\nLors d\'un clic sur un lien hash, le composant `CurrentPathname` sera rendu \xe0 nouveau, m\xeame s\'il n\'utilise pas l\'attribut `hash` \uD83D\uDE05.\\n\\n:::tip\\n\\nChaque fois qu\'un hook renvoie des donn\xe9es que tu n\'affiches pas, pense aux re-renders de React. Si tu ne fais pas attention, un simple appel `useLocation()` au sommet de ton app React peut nuire aux performances de ton application.\\n\\n:::\\n\\n:::info\\n\\nLe but n\'est pas de critiquer React-Router, mais plut\xf4t d\'illustrer le probl\xe8me. `useLocation()` est simplement un bon candidat pour cr\xe9er cet article interactif. Tes propres hooks React et d\'autres librairies tierces pourraient \xe9galement avoir ce probl\xe8me.\\n\\n:::\\n\\n## `useSyncExternalStore` \xe0 la rescousse?\\n\\nLa [documentation officielle](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#usesyncexternalstore) dit:\\n\\n> useSyncExternalStore is a hook recommended for reading and subscribing from external data sources in a way that\u2019s compatible with concurrent rendering features like selective hydration and time slicing.\\n> This method returns the value of the store and accepts three arguments:\\n>\\n> - `subscribe`: function to register a callback that is called whenever the store changes.\\n> - `getSnapshot`: function that returns the current value of the store.\\n> - `getServerSnapshot`: function that returns the snapshot used during server rendering.\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction useSyncExternalStore<Snapshot>(\\n  subscribe: (onStoreChange: () => void) => () => void,\\n  getSnapshot: () => Snapshot,\\n  getServerSnapshot?: () => Snapshot\\n): Snapshot;\\n```\\n\\nBon, c\'est pas tr\xe8s parlant. Cette [page de doc en beta](https://beta.reactjs.org/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect#subscribing-to-an-external-store) donne un meilleur exemple:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction subscribe(callback) {\\n  window.addEventListener(\\"online\\", callback);\\n  window.addEventListener(\\"offline\\", callback);\\n  return () => {\\n    window.removeEventListener(\\"online\\", callback);\\n    window.removeEventListener(\\"offline\\", callback);\\n  };\\n}\\n\\nfunction useOnlineStatus() {\\n  return useSyncExternalStore(\\n    subscribe,\\n    () => navigator.onLine,\\n    () => true\\n  );\\n}\\n\\nfunction ChatIndicator() {\\n  const isOnline = useOnlineStatus();\\n  // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIl s\'av\xe8re que l\'historique du navigateur peut \xe9galement \xeatre consid\xe9r\xe9 comme une source de donn\xe9es externe. Voyons comment utiliser `useSyncExternalStore` avec React-Router !\\n\\n## Implementation de `useHistorySelector()`\\n\\nReact-Router expose tout ce dont on a besoin pour utiliser `useSyncExternalStore`:\\n\\n- acc\xe8s \xe0 l\'historique avec [`useHistory()`](https://v5.reactrouter.com/web/api/Hooks/usehistory)\\n- abonnement aux mises \xe0 jour avec [`history.listen(callback)`](https://github.com/remix-run/history/blob/main/docs/api-reference.md#history.listen)\\n- acc\xe8s \xe0 l\'\xe9tat actuel avec [`history.location`](https://github.com/remix-run/history/blob/main/docs/api-reference.md#historylocation)\\n\\n:::caution\\n\\nCe site web utilise React-Router v5 : la solution sera diff\xe9rente pour React-Router v6 ([voir](https://twitter.com/Zh0uzi/status/1567523679604539405)).\\n\\n:::\\n\\nL\'impl\xe9mentation de `useHistorySelector()` est relativement simple:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction useHistorySelector(selector) {\\n  const history = useHistory();\\n  return useSyncExternalStore(history.listen, () =>\\n    selector(history)\\n  );\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUtilisons-le dans notre application:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction CurrentPathname() {\\n  const pathname = useHistorySelector(\\n    (history) => history.location.pathname\\n  );\\n  return <div>{pathname}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction CurrentHash() {\\n  const hash = useHistorySelector(\\n    (history) => history.location.hash\\n  );\\n  return <div>{hash}</div>;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n<AppFixed />\\n\\nMaintenant, quand on clique sur un lien hash, le composant `CurrentPathname` ne sera **plus re-rendu** !\\n\\n## Un autre exemple: `scrollY`\\n\\nIl existe un grand nombre de sources de donn\xe9es externes auxquelles nous pouvons nous abonner, pour lesquelles l\'impl\xe9mentation d\'un syst\xe8me de s\xe9lection pourrait te permettre d\'optimiser les rendus de React.\\n\\nPar exemple, supposons que nous voulons utiliser la position `scrollY` d\'une page. On peut impl\xe9menter ce hook React:\\n\\n```tsx\\n// Une fonction constante permet d\'\xe9viter la re-souscription\\n// En pratique, c\'est souvent pas un probl\xe8me\\nfunction subscribe(onStoreChange) {\\n  global.window?.addEventListener(\\"scroll\\", onStoreChange);\\n  return () =>\\n    global.window?.removeEventListener(\\n      \\"scroll\\",\\n      onStoreChange\\n    );\\n}\\n\\nfunction useScrollY(selector = (id) => id) {\\n  return useSyncExternalStore(\\n    subscribe,\\n    () => selector(global.window?.scrollY),\\n    () => undefined\\n  );\\n}\\n```\\n\\nNous pouvons maintenant utiliser ce hook, avec un s\xe9lecteur optionnel:\\n\\n```tsx\\nfunction ScrollY() {\\n  const scrollY = useScrollY();\\n  return <div>{scrollY}</div>;\\n}\\n\\nfunction ScrollYFloored() {\\n  const to = 100;\\n  const scrollYFloored = useScrollY((y) =>\\n    y ? Math.floor(y / to) * to : undefined\\n  );\\n  return <div>{scrollYFloored}</div>;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n<ScrollApp />\\n\\nFais d\xe9filer la page et regarde comment les composants ci-dessus sont re-rendus ? L\'un d\'eux re-render beaucoup plus souvent!\\n\\n:::info\\n\\nLorsque tu n\'as pas besoin d\'un niveau de pr\xe9cision de 1 pixel pour `scrollY`, retourner une valeur large comme `scrollY` peut aussi \xeatre consid\xe9r\xe9 comme retourner trop de donn\xe9es. Il faut envisager de retourner une valeur plus \xe9troite.\\n\\nPar exemple : un hook `useResponsiveBreakpoint()` qui ne renvoie qu\'un ensemble limit\xe9 de valeurs (`small`, `medium` ou `large`) sera plus optimis\xe9 qu\'un hook `useViewportWidth()`.\\n\\nSi un composant React ne traite que les \xe9crans `large` de mani\xe8re diff\xe9rente, tu peux cr\xe9er un hook `useIsLargeScreen()` encore plus restreint, retournant un bool\xe9en.\\n\\n:::\\n\\n## Conclusion\\n\\nJ\'esp\xe8re que cet article t\'as convaincu de jeter un coup \u0153il \xe0 `useSyncExternalStore()`. Je trouve que ce hook est actuellement sous-utilis\xe9 dans l\'\xe9cosyst\xe8me React, et m\xe9rite un peu plus d\'attention. Il existe de nombreuses sources de donn\xe9es externes auxquelles on peut s\'abonner.\\n\\nSi tu n\'as pas encore mis \xe0 jour ton app vers React 18, il y a un shim npm [use-sync-external-store](https://www.npmjs.com/package/use-sync-external-store) que tu peux d\xe9j\xe0 utiliser aujourd\'hui dans tes applications. Il existe \xe9galement un export `use-sync-external-store/with-selector` au cas o\xf9 tu as besoin de retourner une valeur non primitive m\xe9mois\xe9e."},{"id":"records-and-tuples-for-react","metadata":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/records-and-tuples-for-react","source":"@site/articles/old/2020-07-31-records-and-tuples-for-react-developers/index.mdx","title":"Records & Tuples for React","description":".Records & Tuples for React... and how they are much more than immutable data structures.","date":"2020-07-31T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.47,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Editeur - Mainteneur de Docusaurus","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","page":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/authors/slorber"},"socials":{"x":"https://x.com/sebastienlorber"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"records-and-tuples-for-react","title":"Records & Tuples for React","description":".Records & Tuples for React... and how they are much more than immutable data structures.","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"useSyncExternalStore - L\'API React sous-estim\xe9e","permalink":"/fr/articles/useSyncExternalStore-the-underrated-react-api"},"nextItem":{"title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","permalink":"/fr/articles/using-expo-in-gatsby"}},"content":"**Records & Tuples**, a very interesting **[proposal](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-record-tuple)**, has just reached **[stage 2](https://twitter.com/robpalmer2/status/1286040041089904640)** at **TC39**.\\n\\nThey bring **deeply immutable data structures** to JavaScript.\\n\\nBut don\'t overlook their **equality properties**, that are <u>**VERY**</u> interesting for **React**.\\n\\nA whole category of **React bugs** are related to **unstable object identities**:\\n\\n- **Performance**: re-renders that could be avoided\\n- **Behavior**: useless effect re-executions, infinite loops\\n- **API surface**: unability to express when a stable object identity matters\\n\\nI will explain the basics of **Records & Tuples**, and how they can solve **real world React issues**.\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/records-and-tuples-for-react)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/records-and-tuples-for-react)"},{"id":"using-expo-in-gatsby","metadata":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/using-expo-in-gatsby","source":"@site/articles/old/2020-05-11-using-expo-in-gatsby/index.mdx","title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","description":"Using Expo in Gatsby... or how to use cross-platform components in a MDX blog post","date":"2020-05-11T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.25,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Editeur - Mainteneur de Docusaurus","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","page":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/authors/slorber"},"socials":{"x":"https://x.com/sebastienlorber"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"using-expo-in-gatsby","title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","description":"Using Expo in Gatsby... or how to use cross-platform components in a MDX blog post","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Records & Tuples for React","permalink":"/fr/articles/records-and-tuples-for-react"},"nextItem":{"title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","permalink":"/fr/articles/atomic-css-in-js"}},"content":"You probably heard of [React-Native-Web](https://github.com/necolas/react-native-web), allowing to render **React-Native views on the web**.\\n\\n**So, what about using React-Native in a Gatsby website?**\\n\\nThis post is a **proof-of-concept**: it contains **React-Native** and **Expo** interactive components, embedded directly into [this article](https://github.com/slorber/sebastienlorber.com/tree/master/content/posts/2020-05-11-using-expo-in-gatsby) (using [MDX](https://github.com/mdx-js/mdx)), of my [open-source](https://github.com/slorber/sebastienlorber.com) Gatsby site.\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/using-expo-in-gatsby)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/using-expo-in-gatsby)"},{"id":"atomic-css-in-js","metadata":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/atomic-css-in-js","source":"@site/articles/old/2020-04-27-atomic-css-in-js/index.mdx","title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","description":"Atomic CSS-in-JS... or how to scale your CSS-in-JS.","date":"2020-04-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.46,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Editeur - Mainteneur de Docusaurus","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","page":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/authors/slorber"},"socials":{"x":"https://x.com/sebastienlorber"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"atomic-css-in-js","title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","description":"Atomic CSS-in-JS... or how to scale your CSS-in-JS.","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Using Expo in Gatsby","permalink":"/fr/articles/using-expo-in-gatsby"},"nextItem":{"title":"Handling API request race conditions in React","permalink":"/fr/articles/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react"}},"content":"With recent production deployments from Facebook and Twitter, I think a new trend is slowly growing: atomic CSS-in-JS.\\n\\nIn this post, we\'ll see what atomic CSS is, how it relates to functional / utility-first CSS like TailwindCSS, and that big players are adopting it in their modern React codebases.\\n\\nAs I\'m not a expert of this subject, don\'t expect a deep dive about the pros and cons. I just hope you get an idea about what it\'s about.\\n\\n**Note**: Atomic CSS is not really related to [Atomic Design](https://atomicdesign.bradfrost.com/).\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/atomic-css-in-js)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/atomic-css-in-js)"},{"id":"handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react","metadata":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react","source":"@site/articles/old/2019-08-30-handling-race-conditions-in-react/index.mdx","title":"Handling API request race conditions in React","description":"Handling API request race conditions in React... or how to avoid rendering the wrong data","date":"2019-08-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[],"readingTime":0.24,"hasTruncateMarker":false,"authors":[{"name":"S\xe9bastien Lorber","title":"Editeur - Mainteneur de Docusaurus","url":"https://sebastienlorber.com","page":{"permalink":"/fr/articles/authors/slorber"},"socials":{"x":"https://x.com/sebastienlorber"},"imageURL":"https://github.com/slorber.png","key":"slorber"}],"frontMatter":{"slug":"handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react","title":"Handling API request race conditions in React","description":"Handling API request race conditions in React... or how to avoid rendering the wrong data","authors":["slorber"],"twitterThreadUrl":"https://slo.im/thread","image":"./images/hero.png","isTranslationMissing":true},"unlisted":false,"prevItem":{"title":"Atomic CSS-in-JS","permalink":"/fr/articles/atomic-css-in-js"}},"content":"Many blog articles talk about loading api/async data in React apps, with `componentDidMount`, `useEffect`, Redux, Apollo...\\n\\nYet, all those articles are **generally optimistic**, and never mention something important to consider: race conditions could happen, and your UI may end up in an **inconsistent state**.\\n\\n[![hero](./images/hero.png)](https://sebastienlorber.com/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react)\\n\\n\uD83D\uDD17 [**Read More**](https://sebastienlorber.com/handling-api-request-race-conditions-in-react)"}]}}')}}]);